<h2 id="list-of-neighbors">List of Neighbors</h2><p><br></p><p>For each node, record which other node neighbor this node. This representation is quite efficient in memory usage. </p><p><br></p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64,"></p><p>Image taken from the slides of the TU Delft Electrical engineering Master course on Networking (EE4C06)</p><p><br></p><p><br></p><h2 id="adjacency-matrix-(﻿aaa﻿)">Adjacency Matrix (<span class="ql-formula" data-value="A">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">A</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>)</h2><p><br></p><p>A boolean matrix can be used to record for every node, to which other node it is connected. The diagonal is zero when there are no self-connections. The matrix is symmetric over the diagonal when the graph is undirected.</p><p><br></p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64,"></p><p>Image taken from the slides of the TU Delft Electrical engineering Master course on Networking (EE4C06)</p><p><br></p><p><br></p><h2 id="incidence-matrix-(﻿bbb﻿)">Incidence matrix (<span class="ql-formula" data-value="B">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span style="margin-right: 0.05017em;" class="mord mathdefault">B</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>)</h2><p><br></p><p>A different kind of matrix can be  used to record for every node, which edge is connected to it. In the images below, a graph is shown and its incidence matrix. every row is a node, and every column is an edge. </p><p><br></p><p>Every column contains a <span class="ql-formula" data-value="1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>  and a <span class="ql-formula" data-value="-1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">-1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.72777em; vertical-align: -0.08333em;"></span><span class="mord">−</span><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>. The <span class="ql-formula" data-value="-1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">-1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.72777em; vertical-align: -0.08333em;"></span><span class="mord">−</span><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>  is the node which the edge goes out, and the <span class="ql-formula" data-value="1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>  is the node where the edge goes to.  It is common to write a <span class="ql-formula" data-value="1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>  in both the outgoing and incoming place when the graph is undirected.</p><p><br></p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64,"></p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64,"></p><p>Images taken from the slides of the TU Delft Electrical engineering Master course on Networking (EE4C06)</p><p><br></p><p><br></p><h2 id="laplacian-matrix-(﻿qqq﻿)">Laplacian Matrix (<span class="ql-formula" data-value="Q">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8777699999999999em; vertical-align: -0.19444em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">Q</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>)</h2><p><br></p><p>A Laplacian matrix combines both the Adjacency and Incidence Matrix. Laplacian matrices are square like Adjacency Matrices, and are (as  far as I can see) only defined for undirected graphs. <span class="ql-formula" data-value="Q">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8777699999999999em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord"><span style="margin-right: 0.05017em;" class="mord mathdefault">B</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.8413309999999999em;"><span class="" style="top: -3.063em; On this diagonal, the degree of every node is given. The degree of a node is the number of connections to it (in an undirected way). Therefore, this is equal to the sum of each row in the Adjacency matrix. </p><p><br></p><p>In mathematical notation:</p><p><br></p><p><span class="ql-formula" data-value="\Delta=diag\left(d_1\ d_2\ \ldots d_N\right)">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mo>…</mo><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>N</mi></msub><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\Delta=diag\left(d_1\ d_2\ \ldots d_N\right)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; 	      [1 0 1] --&gt; sum = 2

It is created from the adjacency matrix.
